A TRAIN CREW DETECTED THE ODOR OF CHLORINE DURING SWITCHING OPERATION. THE CREW NOTIFIED YARDMASTER, WHO IN TURN, NOTIFIED THE NEARBY SHIPPER. HAZMAT EMERGENCY RESPONDERS DETERMINED THAT TANK CAR ACFX 19847, RESIDUE: LAST CONTAINED CHLORINE, 2.3, UN1017, WAS LEAKING DUE TO A LOOSE BOLT ON A LIQUID LINE VALVE.  AFTER THE BOLT WAS TIGHTENED, THE LEAK STOPPED, AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT APPROXIMATELY 0.5 MILES TO FINAL DESTINATION.  THE SHIPPER ADVISED THAT A NITROGEN BLANKET WAS APPLIED TO THE CAR PRIOR TO THE RESIDUE MOVEMENT.  THE SHIPPER LATER ADVISED THAT THE WEIGHT OF PRODUCT IN THE CAR AT FINAL DESTINATION WAS LESS THAN 1 POUND.

column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTES WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. LOCATED AT 1910 RUSSELL STREET IN BALTIMORE, MD TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CONNECTICUT, INC. LOCATED AT 51 BRODERICK ROAD IN BRISTOL, CT.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER STOPPED AT MARYLAND HOUSE TRUCK STOP LOCATED ON I-95 NORTH IN ABERDEEN, MD IN ORDER TO OBTAIN REST.  DURING THIS STOP, THE DRIVER CONDUCTED A ROUTINE TIRE AND LOAD CHECK AND DISCOVERED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING AREA OF THE TRUCK STOP.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE USING SPEEDIDRY AND CONTACTED HIS HOME DISPATCHER WHO, IN-TURN, DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW TO THE SCENE.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, THE TRAILER WAS ENTERED AND IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE CONTAINER HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY A WELD USED TO SECURE THE TRAILER'S CONTAINMENT SYSTEM.  THE CREW THEN OVERPACKED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM, CONTAINERIZED THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL USED TO ABSORB THE MATERIAL RELEASED ONTO THE PAVEMENT AND SPREAD SPEEDI DRY ON THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER.  THE VEHICLE WAS THEN DIRECTED BACK TO THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION BY THE MARYLAND DEPARTMENT OF THE ENVIRONMENT WHERE THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WAS DECONTAMINATED.  ALL SPILL DEBRIS GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT WAS PLACED INTO STORAGE AT THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION PENDING DISPOSAL.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED.  ALL LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND WILL TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.  IN ADDITION, THE WELDS USED TO SECURE THE CONTAINMENT SYSTEM TO THIS TRAILER WILL BE INSPECTED AND ANY PROTRUSIONS CAPABLE OF DAMAGING THE LADING OF THE VEHICLE WILL BE REPAIRED.

CONTAINER OOCL-312316 WAS LOADED ON BOARD THE VESSEL IN SAN PABLO, CA.  ON ARRIVAL IN OAKLAND, IT WAS DISCOVERED BY THE VESSEL'S CHIEF MATE TO HAVE MATERIAL SEEPING THROUGH THE CONTAINER FLOOR BOARDS.  AFTER TIE UP OF THE VESSEL, THE CONTAINER WAS DISCHARGED TO THE STRINGER AND SECURED TO PREVENT FURTHER CONTAMINATION TO THE SURROUNDING AREA.  WHEN THE CONTAINER WAS DEVANNED BY INTERNATIONAL TECHNOLOGY CORPORATION, ONE DRUM WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE A LEAK IN THE TOP CHIME.  THE DAMAGE TO THE DRUM WAS CAUSED BY THE DRUM RUBBING AGAINST THE WALL OF THE CONTAINER.  ALL NECESSARY CLEAN UP WAS ACCOMPLISHED UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF THE US COAST GUARD. (THIS SHIPMENT WAS A SHIPPER'S LOAD AND COUNT.  AMERICAN PRESIDENT LINES BEAR NO RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE IMPROPER LOADING PRACTICES.)

OUR DRIVER HAD APPROACHED A CURVE TOO FAST AND LOST CONTROL OF HIS UNIT. THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER RAN OFF THE ROAD AND THEN STOPPED IN A BANK. THE FIRE DEPT AND THE POLICE SHOWED UP AT SCENE, OUR DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL AND A CLEAN UP RESPONSE UNIT WAS CALLED.  APPROXIMATELY 20 TONS WAS SPILLED OR 1/2 OF LOAD. TRAIN 195 WAS STOPPED ON THR MAIN TRACK AT ACADEMY, COLORADO, ON THE DENVER SUBDIVISION, JOINT TIMETABLE, LINE SEGMENT 1506. SANTA FE RAILWAY TRACK INSPECTOR OBSERVED GATX 25160 LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM.  INSPECTION OF THE CAR BY BURLINGTON NORTHERN REVEALED THAT A WELD NEAR THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE SKID PLATE OF ONE OF THE COMPARTMENTS HAD FAILED.  THE CARL GATX 25160, WAS MOVED TO MONUMENT, COLORADO, AND THE AFFECTED COMPARTMENT WAS OFF-LOADED BY THE CONSIGNEE, ASHLAND CHEMICAL.

SWITCH CREW OF 315G459 NOTICED A STRONG AMMONIA ODOR ORIGINATING FROM TANK CAR GATX 41221.  INSPECTED OF TANK CAR BY BURLINGTON NORTHERN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EMERGENCY RESPONDER REVEALED THAT THE GAGING ROD'S PACKING GRAND NUT ON GATX 41221 WAS LOOSES AND LEAKING AMMONIA.  RESPONDER TIGHTENED PACKING GLAND NUT WHICH STOPPED THE RELEASE.

SWITCH CREW 3036 OBSERVED TANK CAR CRCX 30009 LEAKING FROM THE MANWAY. INSPECTION OF CRCX 30009 BY BURLINGTON NORTHERN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONDER REVEALED MANWAY BOLTS WERE LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT.  RESPONDER TIGHTENED MANWAY BOLTS, WHICH DID NOT STOP THE RELEASE.  BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVE INSPECTOR WAS NOTIFIED AND ARRIVED WITH A NEW MANWAY GASKET. THE GASKET WAS INSTALLED AND THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED, WHICH CORRECTED THE PROBLEM.

ON 12/29/94 AT 0945 HOURS, ASHLAND CHEMICAL DELIVERED A 2000 GALLON LOAD OF NAPTHA (SOLVENT 140) VIA CARGO TANK TRUCK TO ALLIED PETROLEUM'S BULK TERMINAL IN RENO, NV.  TERMS OF THE DELIVERY REQUIRED THAT WE TRANSFER THE NAPTHA FROM OUR CARGO TANK TO ALLIED CARGO TANK VIA A CHEMICAL TRANSFER HOSE THROUGH THE MANWAY ON TOP OF ALLIED TANK.  TRANSFER TOOK PACED INSIDE ALLIED CONCRETE CONTAINMENT AREA.  AN ALLIED EMPLOYEE HOLDING THE HOSE LOST HIS GRIP WHEN OUR DRIVER STARTED TO PUMP THE NAPTHA.  APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS SPILLED ON THE CONCRETE.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY ALLIED'S EMPLOYEES USING ABSORBANT AND RETAINED ON ALLIED SITE.

column17: HUNT J B SPECIAL COMMODITIES I
column168: THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED AROUND 2010 HOURS ON NOVEMBER 29, 1994 NEAR PALESTINE, ARKANSAS ON INTERSTATE 40. OUR DRIVER DISCOVERED MATERIAL HAD LEAKED FROM THE FRONT OF THE CARGO TANK AFTER STOPPING DURING A ROUTINE TIRE CHECK. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO OUR OFFICE AND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE. OUR EMERGENCY COORDINATOR REPORTED THE REQUIRED INFORMATION TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER REFERENCE REPORT #271346. THIS LEAKAGE WAS A RESULT OF TWO MISSING HALF INCH PIPE PLUGS FROM THE TOP NEAR THE FRONT OF THE TANK. THE MATERIAL HAD SLOSHED OUT THESE TWO PLUGS DURING TRANSIT. THESE TWO PLUGS WERE EVIDENTLY REMOVED FROM ONE OF TWO IDENTICAL, RECENTLY PURCHASED, MC 307 CARGO TANKS AFTER THE REQUIRED PRESSURE, EXTERNAL, INTERNAL AND LEAKAGE TEST WERE PERFORMED BY THE MANUFACTURER, NOVA FABRICATING, INC. DURING OCTOBER OF THIS YEAR. AFTER MANUFACTURE, THIS TANK WAS EQUIPMENT WITH AN INTERNAL AGITATOR SYSTEM. IT IS NOT KNOWN WHEN OR WHO REMOVE THE PLUGS AND FAILED TO REPLACE THEM. THE LEAK OCCURRED DURING THE FIRST LOAD. THE TANKER WAS CARRYING "WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID, 3, UN1993 PG111 RQ [D006, D007, D008, D009,] (ACETONE, XYLENE, TOLUENE) <OZONE DEPLETOR> AS A WASTE FUEL FOR CEMENT KILNS. IT IS BELIEVED THAT MOST OF THE MATERIAL SPILLED WHEN THE DRIVER STOPPED FOR THE TIRE CHECK. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON HAD LEAKED ONTO THE GROUND. MATERIAL PARTIALLY COVERED THE FRONT PORTION OF THE CARGO TANK AND THE TRUCK FRAME. THE MATERIAL WAS WIPED FROM THE VEHICLE AND OFF THE CONCRETE WITH PAPER TOWELS WHICH WERE PLACED IN THE TANK. THIS TANK WILL AGITATE AND UNLOAD SEMI-SOLID MATERIALS ALONG WITH LIQUIDS. NO MATERIAL LEAKED NEAR ANY WATERWAY. THE MISSING PLUGS WERE REPLACED AND THE TANK WAS RETURNED TO SERVICE. THE OTHER NEWLY PURCHASED TANK WAS CLOSELY CHECKED FOR MISSING PLUGS. THE FRONT PLUGS WERE NOT MISSING FROM THIS TANK.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER WAS EXITING INTERSTATE 100 AT MILE MARKER 872 JUST WEST OF ORANGE, TEXAS. THE TRUCK AND TRAILER ROLLED OVER INTO A DITCH ADJACENT TO THE ACCESS ROAD. AN INVESTIGATION OF THE ACCIDENT HAD DETERMINED THAT EXCESSIVE SPEED WAS THE SOLE CAUSE. THE DRIVER SHOULD HAVE COMPENSATED FOR THE LOCATIOIN, WEATHER CONDITIONS, AND SLOSHING LOAD; THE APPROPRIATE SPEED WOULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS ACCIDENT. DRIVER WAS LOADING THE #2 COMPARTMENT ON TRAILER WHICH IS 2000 GALLONS CAPACITY. HE ENTERED 2500 GALLONS ON THE METER. THE CONOCO PIPELINE IS STILL TOP LOADING AND BEFORE THE DRIVER COULD GET THE PUMP SHUT OFF, APPROXIMATELY 80 TO 175 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL HAD RUN OVER. THE OVERFILL WAS CONTAINED IN THE PIPELINE SUMP. THE DRIVER WAS REPRIMANDED AND GIVEN RETRAINING ON PROPER LOADING PROCEDURES.

DRIVER WAS SLEEPING AT THE REST AREA; THE STATE POLICE DISCOVERED THE TRAILER DRIPPING AT THE VALVE. THE STATE POLICE CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THEY EVACUATED THE REST AREA UNTIL THE HAZMAT OFFICER ARRIVED, HE OPENED THE REST AREA AFTER HE ARRIVED, THE TRAILER WAS CLEANED IN CHICAGO IL. AND SOME MATERIAL TURNED TO A RUBBER SUBSTANCE, SOME OF THE MATERIAL WAS IN THE INTER VALVE PREVENTING A GOOD SEAL. THE OUTER VALVE HAD SOME SMALL PIECES OF MATERIAL PREVENTING IT FROM CLOSING, THE GASKET AROUND THE OUTER VALVE WAS BENT WHEN IT WAS INSTALLED AT THE TANK WASH, THE VALVE WAS LEAKING AT THE CLAMP THAT HOLD THE VALVE TO THE TRAILER. ALTHOUGH THE DRIPPING CEASED THE OFFICER AND I MADE THE DECISION TO UNLOAD THE TRAILER INTO ANOTHER TRAILER. A TRAILER WAS DEPATCHED TO THE SCENE AND THE LOAD WAS TRANSFERED AND BROUGHT TO ST LOUIS, MO.

THE PUMP ON THE TRAILER HAS TWO OUTLETS, ONE ON EITHER SIDE OF TRAILER. THE DRIVER WAS PUMPING OFF, USING THE LEFT SIDE OUTLET. HE HAD JUST STARTED THE PUMP WHEN THE CAP ON THE RIGHT SIDE BLEW OFF. THE COMPANY HAS A POLICY THAT THE EARS ON THE COMELOCK FITTINGS HAVE TO BE TIED DOWN SO THEY DON'T COME LOOSE. THE DRIVER WAS APPARENTLY IN A HURRY AND DIDN'T CHECK THE CAP ON THE RIGHT SIDE. THE DRIVER WAS REPRIMANDED AND GIVEN TIME OFF.

DURING TRANSPORTATION FROM THE CUSTOMER TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN RALEIGH, NC FACILITY, 1 FIFTEEN GALLON CONTAINER OF PHOTOGRAPHIC WASTE OVERTURNED, CAUSING THE LID TO COME OFF.  ALL OF THE WASTE EXCEPT FOR 1 QUART WAS CONTAINED ON THE TRUCK.  APPROXIMATELY 1 QUART SPILLED OUT OF THE TRUCKS CONTAINMENT TRENCH WHILE THE TRUCK WAS WAS AT THE SAFETY-KLEEN RALEIGH, NC FACILITY.  ALL OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT TOWELLS.  NO ONE WAS INJURED DURING THE INCIDENT, AND NONE OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL REACHED WATER OR SOIL.

AS DRIVER WAITED TO ENTER OUR LANDFILL FACILITIES, HE LOOSENED THE WING NUT ON THE BACK OF THE TRAILER.  THE WING NUTS KEEP THE BACK GATE CLOSED IN CASE THE AIR LOCKING FAIL.  AS THE PROCEEDED TO MOVE FORWARD INTO THE LANDFILL, THE GATE OPENED SLIGHTLY & ALLOWED SOME OF THE FILTER CAKE TO SPRINKLE ONTO THE GRAVEL ROAD IMMEDIATELY OUTSIDE THE LANDFILL GATES. ANOTHER TRUCK WAITING TO PULL IN WAS BEHIND THE AFORMENTIONED TRUCK.  HE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE DRIVER OF THE SPILL.  THE LANDFILL MGR WAS NOTIFIED & CLEANUP BEGAN IMMEDIATELY.  A FRONT END SCOOPER PICKED UP THE GRAVEL & FILTERCAKE (2.5YDS0 & DEPOSITED THE MAIL INTO THE LANDFILL.  THE DRIVER & ALL OTHER LANDFILL DRIVERS WERE SPECIFICALLY TOLD VERBALLY & IN WRITING NOT TO LOOSEN THE WING NUTS PRIOR TO ENTERING THE LANDFILL. FUTURE OCCURANCEY WOULD NOT BE TOLERATED.

column14: EXIT RAMP I 285 NORTH AT GA 12
column168: THE TRUCK WAS INVOLVED IN A TRAFFIC ACCIDENT AT THE TOP OF THE NORTHBOUND I-285 EXIT RAMP AT COVINGTON HIGHWAY, GA-12, WHICH BLOCKED BOTH RAMP LANES FOR APPROXIMATELY FOUR HOURS.  I-285 REMAINED OPEN DURING THIS INCIDENT. THE ACCIDENT CAUSED THE LOAD TO SHIFT AND THE FRONT RIGHT DOOR FAILED. THE FRONT LOAD LOCK BAR CAME LOOSE DUE TO THE FAILURE OF THE RIGHT DOOR AND THE BAR PUNCTURED A DRUM, STILL UPRIGHT, ON THE FAR LEFT SIDE JUST TO THE REAR OF THE LOAD LOCK BAR.  HEPCO INCORPORATED, AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, NEUTRALIED AND ABSORBED THE LEAKING ACID SOLUTION WITH LIME. BOTH THE INSIDE OF THE VAN AND THE ROADWAY WERE TREATED.  THE DAMAGED DRUM AND ALL OF THE SPILL CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED IN 85 GALLON RECOVERY DRUMS AND TAKEN TO NIAGARA NATIONAL FACILITY ON HILLS AVE.  THE OTHER CARGO WAS TRANSFERRED TO A SECOND TRUCK AND RETURNED TO NIAGARA NATIONAL. THE DAMAGED TRUCK WAS THEN TOWED TO A REPAIR FACILITY.

AT 09:45 HOURS ON DECEMBER 14TH, A GREENWICH YARD SWITCH CREW NOTICED VAPORS COMING FROM UTLX 802742 IN TRAIN ALPG3.  CONRAIL REQUESTED BOE SR. INSPECTOR A.W. RICHTER TO INSPECT THE TANK CAR SINCE HE WAS IN THE AREA. MR. RICHTER NOTED THAT THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED, THE FRANGIBLE DISC WAS UP-SIDE-DOWN IN THE SAFETY VENT, AND THE CAR WAS STENCILED WITH INCORRECT SPECIFICATION.  REPRESENTATIVES FROM VISTA CHEMICAL REPLACED THE 135# DISC AND THE SAFETY VENT CLOSURE FLANGE.  THEY NEUTRALIZED PRODUCT ON THE CAR AND OBSERVED THE CAR IN MOVEMENT TO ENSURE THAT THEIR REPAIRS WERE ADEQUATE.

column168: DRIVER IN THE ENROUTE TO CONSIGNEE_ DRIVER TRAVELING NORTH ON I-196 MILE MARKER 17 DRIVER STRUCK GUARDRAIL ON RIGHT SIDE OF INTERSTATE.  CROSSED OVER HIGHWAY INTO THE MEDIAN.  ROLLED OVER ON TO DRIVER'S SIDE WITH TRACTORON HIGHWAY AND TRAILER IN MEDIAN APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED DUE TO THE ROLLOVER.  DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO HOSPITAL- BROKEN COLLAR BONE, BROKEN SHOULDER.  TREATED AND RELEASED.  DRIVER DOING WELL SINCE ACCIDENT. PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP AND CONTAINED.  REMAINING PRODUCT IN TRAILER WAS TRANSFERRED SUCCESSFULLY TO ANOTHER TRAILER.

DRIVER IN THE PROCESS OF LOADING, RECEIVED PAPERWORK FROM LOADER WITH INSTURCTIONS THOUGHT HE COULD LEAVE, WHEN DOING SO DRIVER PULLED OUT WHEN LOADING SPOUT WAS STILL IN TRAILER.  PRODUCT CLEANED UP AND CONTAINED.

PRODUCT IN THE PROCESS OF BEING UNLOADED, DRIVER WAS DISCONNECTING PRODUCT HOSE WHILE PRESSURE STILL REMAINED ON THE LINE. DRIVER WAS UNAWARE OF THIS. LESS THAN ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. PRODUCT FELL ONTO DRIVER'S SHOES AND GROUND. DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO AREA HOSPITAL AND TREATED. DRIVER STILL OFF DUE TO BURN TO FEET.

THE DRIVER WAS DELIVERING FUEL TO THE BULK TANK IN VIRGINIA, MN. HE MISCALCULATED WHAT THE TANK WOULD HOLD AND OVER FILLED THE TANK. THIS COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED HAD THE DRIVER TAKEN MORE TIME TO CALCULATE THE TANK VOLUME. THE RECEIVER OF THE PRODUCT HAD THEIR OWN VACUUM TRUCK AND SPILL ABSORBPTION PRODUCTS WHICH THEY WERE ABLE TO USE IMMEDIATELY TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.

ATER GETTING TANK CLEANED, DRIVER PROCEEDED ONTO SHIPPER. DRIVER FAILED TO CHECK INTERNAL & EXTERNAL VALVES AFTER CLEANING. SHIPPER STARTED TO TOP LOAD TANK W/VALVES OPEN. DRIVER SHUT INTERNAL VALVE AS SOON AS HE NOTICED. SPILLING APPROX 20 GALLONS. DRIVER & SHIPPER PERSONNEL APPLIED QUICK DRY & SCOOPED CONT PRODUCT INTO BARREL FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. AFTER CLOSING VALVES PROPERLY THE COMPLETION OF THE LOAD WENT WITH OUT INCIDENT. NO INJURIES REPORTED.

HUM PERSONNEL WERE DRESSED OUT IN TYVEK SUITS WITH SCBA'S AFTER IT WAS FOUND OUT TO BE SODIUM HYDROXIDE & 50% WATER SOLUTION.  THERE APPEARED TO BE SPENT PRODUCT ON THE GROUND AFTER INSPECTION.  PH WAS TAKEN ON WAS ALSO NOTIFIED BY MICKEY DAVIS AND AGREED TO HAVE ENVIRONMENTAL SPECIALIST, INC TO RESPOND AND HANDLE THE CLEANUP PROCEDURE.  ALAN WOLF FROM ENVIRONMENTAL SPECIALISTS WAS ON SCENE AND WITH SAND ON TOP OF PLASTIC APPROXIMATELY 100 YARDS FROM THE TANKER WITH A SECOND DIKE 20 YARDS PAST THE FIRST.  THE PRODUCT WAS THEN OFF LOADED TO ANOTHER TANKER AND TO BE TRANSPORTED BACK TO PPM, INC 806 GENESSEE K.C. MO. FOR STORAGE.  THE TRAILER WAS THEN UPRIGHTED WITH TOW TRUCKS.  THE AREA WHERE THE PRODUCT WAS SPILLED WAS VACUMED UP AND ENVIRONMENTAL SPECIALISTS WILL REMOVE THE DUMPSTER 12/29/94 DURING DAYLIGHT HOURS.  DAVE WILLIAMS FROM THE EPA WAS CONTACTED BY MICKEY DAVIS AND OK'ED THIS PLAN.  SANTA FE TOW REMOVED THE TRUCK AND TRAILER FORM THE SCENE AND TRANSPORTED THEM BOTH TO PPM, INC. -806 GENESSEE K.C. MO. FOR FURTHER DECON AND STORAGE.

column168: A TRACTOR-TRAILER TRANSPORTING LIQUID NITROGEN WAS TRAVELLING WESTBOUND ON I-20 WHEN IT STRUCK A CAR PARKED ALONGSIDE THE HIGHWAY. THE TRACTOR-TRAILER RODE UP ON THE CAR AND THE TRAILER SEPARATED FROM THE TRACTOR. WHEN THE TRAILER STRUCK THE SHOULDER OF THE HIGHWAY, ONE OF THE FRONT SUPPORT RODS ( A DEVICE TO CENTER THE INNER TANK INSIDE A VACUUM INSULATION JACKET ) TORE LOOSE FROM THE CONTAINER RELEASING THE PRODUCT INTO THE ANNULAR SPACE BETWEEN THE CARGO TANK AND THE OUTER JACKET. THE RELEASE OF LIQUID NITROGEN RAISED THE PRESSURE IN THE ANNULAR SPACE CAUSING A BURSTING DISC TO FUNCTION AND RELEASING NITROGEN TO THE ATMOSPHERE.

column168: THE OPERATOR CONNECTED THE FITTINGS AND HOSE TO THE OUTLET VALVE ON THE STANDPIPE OF THE RAILCAR. THE PRODUCT HOSE WAS THEN CONNECTED TO A TANK TRAILER. THE OPERATOR THEN PRESSURIZED THE CAR. UPON PRESSURIZATION, HE OPENED THE PRODUCT VALVE BUT THE PRODUCT DID NOT FLOW. IN VIOLATION OF ALL OF OUR SAFETY RULES, HE THEN REMOVED THE HOSE AND FITTING FROM THE VALVE. AS HE HAD NOT SHUT OFF THE PRODUCT VALVE OR DEPRESSURIZED THE CAR, THE PRODUCT ERUPTED FROM THE RAILCAR. HE WAS EXPOSED TO THE ACID AND COULD NOT SHUT OFF THE VALVE. ANOTHER WORKER CLIMBED ON TO THE RAILCAR AND SHUT OFF THE PRODUCT VALVE. AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT, ALL PERSONNEL WERE RETRAINED IN UNLOADING PROCEDURES, WITH SEVERE DISCIPLINARY ACTION TO BE TAKEN IF ANY OF THE STEP-BY-STEP PROCEDURES ARE NOT FOLLOWED. SPECIFIC "IN THE FIELD" DEMONSTRATIONS WERE AGAIN HELD TO REINFORCE THE STEP-BY-STEP UNLOADING PROCEDURES THAT WILL BE FOLLOWED.

column168: I, LEROY D FOX, ON DECEMBER 8, 1994, HAD A DELIVERY TO ACF INDUSTRIES IN MILTON, PA. TANK #001A WHICH IS AN OLD 8000 GAL 80" RAILROAD CAR. IT IS AN ABOVE GROUND TANK WHICH IS A PUMP OFF. I WENT TO DELIVERY SITE AND STARTED TO PUMP OFF. MY PUMP DIDN'T SEEM TO BE PUMPING SO I WENT UPON TANK TO CHECK FLOW AND WHILE I WAS UP ON TANK CHECKING, HOSE BLEW OFF PUMP. I LOST APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF FUEL. VIBRATION OF PUMP CAUSED HOSE EARS TO LOOSEN AND BLOW HOSE OFF. THE OFFICE OF FARM & HOME OIL CO AND ACF PERSONNEL RESPONDED WITHIN MINUTES & CLEANED UP THE OIL. THEY ORIGINALLY ORDERED 7300 GALLONS OF OIL FOR THE TANK, WHICH WE DISCOVERED WOULD NOT FIT. WHEN I TOOK PRIOR STICK READING, I THEN CUT ORDER TO 5000 GALLONS. BEFORE READING: 20 1/4". AFTER READING: 64".

BILL GLASSON, CHEMTREC FILE #32447 AND GARY PEAGO, MINNESOTA CORN PROCESSORS, WERE NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTION.

column168: ON DECEMBER 7, 1994, JON MOOTS, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TECHNICIAN, RESPONDED TO A SPILL IN OUR SORT FACILITY, ABX INC. 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO, 45177. UPON ARRIVAL FOUND A WHITE UNMARKED BOX THAT SHOWED SIGNS, THAT THE CONTENTS MAY BE LEAKING. UPON OPENING THE PACKAGE I DISCOVERED THE CONTENTS TO CONTAIN FOUR BOXES OF 10% BUFFERED FORMALIN, WITH MARKINGS FORMALDEHYDE SOLUTION, UN2209. THREE OF THE FOUR BOXES CONTAINED FIFTY, THIRTY ML. CONTAINERS AND ONE BOX CONTAINED THIRTY-FOUR, THIRTY ML. CONTAINERS. THIS BOX CONTAINED THE LEAKING CONTAINERS. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, DISCOVERED EIGHT CASES MARKED AND LABELED, FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O.S. (ISOPROPANOL, ACETONE), UN1993, ALL IN SPEC PACKAGING 12B30. FOUND ONE UNMARKED BOX WITH THE SAME CONTENTS AS THE EIGHT CASES BUT NO MARKINGS OR LABELS. ONE OTHER FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINED SEVENTEEN VIALS CONTAINING 10ML EACH OF BORIC ACID WHICH IS NON REGULATED. THIS SHIPMENT WILL BE KEPT UNDER LOCATED LOCK AND KEY UNTIL INVESTIGATED AND RELEASED BY THE FAA.

ON 12-9-94, AT 0109, SORT SUPERVISOR, DAN MCCOLLUM REPORTED A SHIPMENT EMITING AN ODOR, TO HAZ-MAT DISPATCH. UPON INVESTIGATION OF "C" SORT LOADING AREA A FIBREBOARD BOX WAS DISCOVERED BY HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORDINATOR ADDIE CAMPTON. THE FIBREBOARD BOX WAS FOUND TO HAVE ONE WET CORNER. UPON OPENING THE PACKAGE, IT WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN VARIOUS COSMETICS FOR FACIAL USE. THESE FACIAL COSMETICS SHOWED NO INDICATION OF BEING REGULATED BY D.O.T. HOWEVER, THE PACKAGE WAS ALSO FOUND TO CONTAIN A PERFUME BOTTLE THAT HAD BROKEN, AND THE ENTIRE CONTENTS HAD LEAKED OUT. ALSO, FOUND WITH THE PERFUME WAS A BOTTLE OF NAIL STRENGTHENER WITH THE CONTENTS LISTED ON THE BOTTLE. THE CONTENTS LISTED INDICATED PRODUCTS THAT ARE REGULATED BY THE D.O.T. THE PACKAGE CONTAINED NO ABSORBENT AND THE PERFUME BOTTLE AND THE NAIL STRENGTHNER WERE NOT SECURELY CONTAINED IN THE INNER PACKAGE. FURTHER INVESTIGATION OF THE PACKAGE INDICATED SHIPMENT WAS NOT PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED, AND PROPER CERTIFICATION DID NOT ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THE SHIPMENT LEAKING ARE THE BOTTLES NOT BEING SECURED IN THE PACKAGE. THIS SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD AT ABX ILN HAZ MAT IN THE SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY IN DRUM #A-11 PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.
DISCOVERED LEAKING PACKAGE.  USED DECISION TREE AND FOLLOWED PROCEDURE FOR PROPER CLEANUP AND DISPOSAL ACCORDING TO RESPONSE SHEETS.

THE DRIVER HAD COMPLETED HIS DELIVERY, AND AS HE WAS WINDING UP HIS DELIVERY HOSE, THE SEAL ON THE HOSE REEL SPRANG A SMALL LEAK.  THE FLOW OF OIL WAS STOPPED, AND THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP.  THE SEAL WAS REPLACED.

column168: ONE OF OUR DRIVERS, JAMES WALLACE, WAS ENROUTE TO GABOR ENTERPRISES IN MADISON, OH, WHEN HE OBSERVED A WHITE VAPOR COMING FROM THE REAR RIGHT SIDE OF HIS FLATBED TRAILER.  JAMES IMMEDIATELY MANEUVERED HIS TRACTOR/TRAILER TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD AND STOPPED.  AFTER DONNING PPE, HE CLIMBED ABOARD THE TRAILER, WHERE HE DISCOVERED THAT A 55-GALLON DRUM CONTAINING HYDROCHLORIC ACID HAD DEVELOPED A VERTICAL CRACK NEAR THE BOTTOM, APPROXIMATELY 5 INCHES IN LENGTH.  JAMES TURNED THE DRUM ON ITS SIDE TO PREVENT THE FURTHER RELEASE OF PRODUCT, USED SPILL CONTAINMENT EQUIPMENT FROM HIS SPILL KIT TO CONTAIN THE LIQUID SPILLED, AND INFORMED ANOTHER TRUCK DRIVER VIA TWO-WAY RADIO AS TO WHAT HAD OCCURRED.  JAMES THEN WAITED WITH PERSONNEL FROM THE MADISON FIRE DISTRICT FIRE DEPARTMENT FOR MEMBERS OF JONES CHEMICALS, INC., EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE AND ASSISTED THEM IN THE CLEAN UP PROCESS.  ALL DOT DRUMS ARE VISUALLY INSPECTED PRIOR TO BEING FILLED, AND WE WILL CONTINUE TO ENSURE THIS PROCEDURE IS BEING FOLLOWED.

column168: RECEIVED CALL VIA RADIO AT APPROXIMATELY 0600 FROM GENERAL YARDMASTER D.O. CHANDLER ABOUT VAPOR COMING FROM TOP OF TANK CAR, UTLX 950037, NINE DEEP FROM THE WEST END OF 043 TRACK.  BEFORE I GOT TO THE CAR, I COULD SEE VAPORTS COMING FROM THE DOME.  WHEN I GOT CLOSE ENOUGH TO THE CAR ON THE UPWIND SIDE, I COULD SEE THE POISON PLACARD.  I THEN ADVISED THE GENERAL YARDMASTER TO REMOVE ALL PERSONNEL FROM THE BOWL.  THE WIND WAS FROM THE NORTH TO THE SOUTH.  I THEN WENT TO THE GENERAL OFFICE BUILDING TO GET A HAZMAT SUIT AND SAFETY EQUIPMENT FOR A BETTER LOOK.  I COULD SEE ANYTHING WHEN I OPENED THE DOME COVER FOR VAPORS, BUT CHECKED TO SEE IF ANY MAIN VALVE MIGHT BE OPEN.  I COULD NOT FIND ANY.  I THEN TOLD THE GENERAL YARDMASTER TO CALL CHEMTREC.  AFTER A MEETING AND UPON THEIR ADVICE, THE CAR WAS MOVED AND ISOLATED ON IC STRAIGHT TRACK BY MYSELF AND MR. CLARENCE MILLER, BUT NOT BEFORE ALL PERSONNEL WERE NOTIFIED AND MOVED INTO THE BUILDING ON THE NORTH SIDE.  DUPONT PERSONNEL ARRIVED AND FOUND TEST COCK ON THE SAFETY VALVE WAS OPEN.  IT WAS CLOSED AND VAPORS STOPPED.  THE ONLY WAY THIS COULD HAVE HAPPENED IS A BAG RUPTURE DISC, AND THE TEST VALVE WAS LEFT OPEN.  THE CAR WAS MOVED TO CHEMTECH FOR UNLOADING IN THE A.M. OF DECEMBER 30, 1994, AFTER IT WAS MADE SURE THAT IT WOULD NOT LEAK AGAIN.

DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS 2 DRUMS WERE FOUND THAT WERE LEAKING DUE TO PIN HOLES.  THE TRAILER AND THE MATERIAL THAT LEAKED OUT WAS CLEANED UP IMMEDIATELY USING ABSORBENT.  LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY (REPORT 94-3207) AND THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, RIGHT TO KNOW SECTION (REPORT 94-5114) WERE CONTACTED.
WHILE TRANSPORTING DRUM & MACHINE FROM GARAGE TO TRUCK DOWN AND MACHINE FELL OFF 2 WHEEL AND TRUCK.

DOCKMAN, J SOKOLOWSKI, WAS REMOVING PALLETIZED FREIGHT FROM TRAILER 19-123 USING A FORKLIFT.  HE EXTENDED HIS FORKLIFT BLADES BEYOND THE LENGTH OF THE PALLET AND PUNCTURED A FIBRE DRUM  WHICH WAS LOADED AHEAD OF THE PALLET.  THE FIBRE DRUM CONTAINED THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL- POTASSIUM BROMATE.  MR. SOKOLOWSKI IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED HIS FOREMAN, H. CAVAZOS, WHO IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE OPERATIONS MANGER, DAN MESKILL.  DAN MESKILL INVESTIGATED THE SPILL AND CONTACTED CHEMTREC.  CHEMTREC NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP, CONTAINED IN A PLASTIC BAG AND PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM WAITING DISPOSITION.

ON 2/23/94 AT APPROXIMATELY 0416 HOURS A SPILL WAS REPORTED TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT OF ABX AIR, INC. 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH 45177. THE SPILL WAS LOCATED IN SECONDARY 1 OF OUR SORT FACILITY AT THE SAME ADDRESS. LEE BROOKS/SORT SUPV DISCOVERED THE LEAKING SHIPMENT, AND MARK GRIFFITH/HAZMAT SPILL TECHNICIAN INVESTIGATED IT. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, I, KAREN NICHOLS/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR OF ABX AIR INC. FOUND THE SHIPMENT TO CONTAIN A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL (ETHYL METHACRYLATE). THE SHIPMENT WAS PACKAGED IN A FIBREBOARD BOX WITH NO HAZARDOUS MARKING OR LABELS, NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPERS CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ACCOMPANYING THE SHIPMENT. INSIDE THE FIBREBOARD BOX WAS 1 X 8 OZ PLASTIC BOTTLE WITH A FLIP-TOP FRICTION (SCREW-TYPE) PLASTIC CLOSURE. THIS PLASTIC BOTTLE HAD PACKING PEANUTS ALL AROUND IT. SOME OF THE PEANUTS HAD BEEN DECINAGRADED DUE TO THE PRODUCT THAT LEAKED. THERE WAS NO APPARENT DAMAGE TO THE PLASTIC BOTTLE. A MINIMAL AMOUNT (APPROXIMATELY 0.5 OZ) OF THE MATERIAL LEAKED. ON 12/28/94, A SECOND SHIPMENT FROM THIS SAME 2 X 16 OZ PLASTIC BOTTLES. THERE WAS AN ODOR EMMITTING FROM THE PACKAGE HOWEVER THERE WAS NO VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE. AT 14:00 12/20/94, UNION PACIFIC REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION, DEAN WHITELEY, WAS NOTIFIED WHILE AT SALT LAKE CITY, UT, BY SHARON FISHER, UPRR CLAIMS DEPARTMENT PALESTINE, TX, THAT COFC ISCU 158901 WHILE BEING TRANSLOADED AT PORT OF PORTLAND TERMINAL 6 DISCOVERED TO HAVE PLASTIC DRUMS OF A CORROSIVE LIQUID LEAKING. DURING TRANSFER OPERATION OF CONTAINER, 2 DRUMS OF CORROSIVE LIQUID, NOS (ALKYL DIMETHBENZENE AMMONIUM CHLORIDE) DISCOVERED TO HAVE SMALL AMOUNT PRODUCT ON TOP OF PLASTIC DRUMS THAT HAD LEAKED FROM AROUND THE BUNGS. FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL, PORTLAND, OR, WAS NOTIFIED BY PORT OF PORTLAND TO ASSIST IN THE CLEAN UP.  THE RELEASE OF MATERIAL WAS NOT CAUSED BY THE EXTERIOR DAMAGE TO CONTAINER.  THE PLASTIC DRUMS IN QUESTION WERE OVERPACKED. THERE WERE NO SPECIFICATION MARKINGS OBTAINED FROM THE LEAKING DRUMS. MYRON SALO, PORT OF PORTLAND TERMINAL 6, 503/240-2159, AND BARBARA WILLIAMSON, MITSUI OSK LINES, PORTLAND, OR, 503/226-0135, PROVIDED INFORMATION CONCERNING THIS INCIDENT.

OUR DRIVER WAS NOT AWARE OF THE SEVERITY OF THE SPILL- SEE INCIDENT REPORT THAT FARMERS BRANCH TYPED UP-SAFETY MGR. & GENERAL MGR. DISCUSSED WITH DRIVER VARIOUS WAYS TO STAY ALERT & TO PAY MORE ATTENTION TO WHAT'S GOING ON.  HE SAID IT WAS DARK & HE SAID THAT MAYBE 5-10 GALS.  SPILLED 7 THEY PUT OIL ABSORBANT ON IT.  ON DECEMBER 10, 1994 MIKE BYAN, DRIVER OF FUEL DELIVERY TRUCK FOR REEDER DISTRIBUTION INC., (PO BOX 8237, FT. WORTH, TEXAS) (817/429-5957) OVER-FILLED ABOVE GROUND DIESEL STORAGE TANKS AT AMERICAN FOODSERVICE (214/385-5802) LOCAED AT 4721 SIMONTON, FARMERS BRANCH, TEXAS.  THE ESTIMATED OVERFLOW OF DIESEL SPILLED ONTO A CONCRETE SURFACE WAS 100 GALLONS. THE SPILLED DIESEL EXITED FROM PRIVATE PROPERTY BY WAY OF STORMWATER OUTFALL, ACCUMULATED IN THE STREET GUTTER WITH A SMALL AMOUNT ENTERING THE STORM SEWER INLET AND DISCHARGING INTO FARMER BRANCH CREEK NEAR THE INTERSECTION OF OLIN AND WELCH ROAD.  BEFORE THE CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT AND ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH OFFICER ARRIVED ON THE SCENE, JEFF HOLDER, DELIVERY MANGER WITH AMERICAN FOODSERVICE RESPONDED TO THE EMERGENCY BY PLACING ABSORBENT MATERIAL ON THE SPILLED DIESEL AND DAMMING THE STREET GUTTER TO PREVENT MOST OF THE DIESEL FROM ENTERING THE STORM SEWER INLET.  THE CITY'S ENVIRONMENT HEALTH OFFICER PLACED FLOATING BOOMS IN FARMERS BRANCH CREEK IMMEDIATELY DOWN STREAM FROM THE STORM SEWER DISCHARGE POINT TO CONTAIN THE FLOATING DIESEL IN THE STREAM. LUCIAN M. LABARBA, CHIEF OPERATING OFFICER AT AMERICAN FOODSERVICE, AND JEFF HOLDER, DELIVERY MANAGER, BOTH MOVED QUICKLY AND RESPONSIBLITY DURING THE EMERGENCY.  THE ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH OFFICER ADVISED THAT EITHER AMERICAN FOODSERVICE OR REEDER DISTRIBUTION INC. MUST REPORT THE SPILL AND THE CLEAN-UP TO THE TEXAS NATURAL RESOURCE CONSERVATION COMMISSION. AMERICAN FOODSERVICE RETAINED ALL WASTE DISPOSAL SERVICE TO REMOVE ACCUMULATED DIESEL FROM THE STREET GUTTER ON SIMONTON.  ALL WASTE DISPOSAL ALSO USED THEIR VACCUM TRUCK TO REMOVE THE DIESEL CONTAINED BY THE BOOMS IN FARMERS BRANCH CREEK.  AMERICAN FOODSERVICE REMOVED THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL CONTAINING THE DIESEL FROM THE STREET GUTTER AND FROM THERI PROPERTY AND DISPOSED OF IT PROPERLY.  (PICTURES WERE TAKEN DURING CLEAN-UP) MIKE BYAN, TRUCK DRIVER RESPONSIBLE FOR THE SPILL, WAS ISSUED A COURT CITATION (TICKET) FOR DISCHARGING A POLLUTANT INTO THE CITY'S STORMWATER SYSTEM.

column168: FEDEX COURIER KATHY SKWERES PICKED UP THE DRUM FROM THE SHIPPER AND HAD PROPERLY STOWED IT IN THE BACK OF HER VEHICLE.  DURING HER ROUTE SHE WAS NAUSEATED AND OVERCOME BY ODORS THAT ORIGINATED IN THE DRUM.  KATHY PULLED HER VEHICLE OFF THE ROAD AND NOTIFIED HER DISPATCHER THAT SHE HAD A "SPILL".  FEDEX DANGEROUS GOODS SPECIALIST CHRIS SHAW CALLED ME AND WAS VERIFYING THE EQUIPMENT HE MIGHT NEED IN DEALING WITH THE SPILL (THE PSN OF THE MATERIAL WAS NOT KNOWN TO CHRIS YET).  DURING OUR CONVERSATION, DISPATCH SENT FEDEX EMPLOYEE ED MARTINEZ TO THE SCENE TO RECOVER THE NON-HAZ FREIGHT.  ED ENTERED THE VEHICLE AND WAS IMMEDATELY OVERCOME BY THE FUMES.  KATHY WALKED TO A NEARBY HOUSTON FIRE STATION AND SUMMONED HELP. WHEN CHRIS ARRIVED, BOTH FEDEX EMPLOYEES WERE ON OXYGEN AND THE FIRE DEPT WAS PLACING THE DRUM INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  BOTH KATHY & ED WERE TRANSPORTED VIA AMBULANCE TO HOUSTON'S NORTH EAST HOSPITAL.  BOTH EMPLOYEES WERE TREATED AND RELEASED THAT EVENING.  THE SHIPPER INITIALLY WAS NOT ABLE TO PROVIDE ANY EMERGENCY RESPONSE INFO (I CALLED THE 24 HR RESPONSE NUMBER). SHORTLY I WAS CALLED BACK BY STEVE HANNAH (713-424-5568) WHO GAVE ME THE ER INFO.  THE FREIGHT WAS RELEASED BY THE FAA AND IT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER IN A SALVAGE DRUM.

FERNAU REQUESTED THAT AGENT BOUDREAUX MEET HIM AT DONALDSONVILLE, LA. ON THE FOLLOWING DAY, 12/29/94, AGENT BOUDREAUX MET WITH FERNAU AND AN INSPECTION WAS MADE. PRODUCT WAS ONLY DETECTED WHEN THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER WAS OPENED.  AGENT BOUDREAUX APPLIED THE GAUGING DEVICE PROTECTIVE COVER.  FERNAU CONTACTED ROY SAVOY OF C F INDUSTRIES AT (504) 473-8291 AND ADVISED HIM OF THE LEAKING VALVE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1730 HRS ON 12/29/94, SAVOY ARRIVED WITH A CREW AND REPAIRED THE LEAKING VALVE.
